  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "For instance, eye gaze is typically represented as positions as well as looking directions of each eye in 3D space.",
    "Facial expressions are typically represented as a list of individual values decoding the activation of individual facial muscles or groups of muscles (e.g., raising the inner part of the left eyebrow, pulling the right lip corner etc.).",
    "Data available in different APIs can show close resemblance to or deviate more strongly from scientific categorizations of facial muscle activity such as the Facial Action Coding System (Canedo & Neves, 2019; Ekman & Rosenberg, 2005).",
    "In order to transfer the software to a networked VR situation, the included mock APIs are replaced with the hardware's actual APIs.",
    "The rest of the software can, in principle, remain unchanged."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Data available in different APIs can show close resemblance to or deviate more strongly from scientific categorizations of facial muscle activity such as the Facial Action Coding System (Canedo & Neves, 2019; Ekman & Rosenberg, 2005)."
